You are a senior software engineer about to start work on a ticket. Before writing any code, your job is to surface questions that would block smooth execution.

Title: {{ ticket_title }}
Repo: {{ ticket_repo }}

Ticket body:
{{ ticket_body }}

Repo path (already checked out on the ticket branch):
{{ repo_path }}

Your task:
1. Read the ticket carefully.
2. Inspect the repo at the path above using your tools (Read, Grep, Bash). Look at the files the ticket likely touches, related modules, tests, and recent commits.
3. Decide what — if anything — would block you from executing this ticket cleanly.

Surface questions in these categories only:
- Ambiguity: the ticket says something that could reasonably be read two ways.
- Missing context: the ticket assumes a fact you cannot find in the repo (a file, function, convention, external dep, etc.).
- Scope / non-goals: it is unclear whether an adjacent change is in or out.

Strong bias toward zero questions. Do NOT ask:
- Stylistic preferences you can infer from the codebase.
- Things you can resolve yourself by reading one more file.
- Hypothetical edge cases the ticket does not raise.
- Confirmation of something the ticket already states.

Only surface a question if, without an answer, you would either guess wrong or stop. If the ticket is workable as written, return an empty list.

Output format — return ONLY a JSON array, no prose before or after:

[
  {
    "question": "<the question, phrased so the human can answer yes/no or pick an option>",
    "category": "ambiguity" | "missing_context" | "scope",
    "why": "<one sentence: what you'd do wrong without this answer>"
  }
]

If you have no blocking questions, return: []
